'''Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine''' (若宮八幡社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Kitsuki|ja|杵築市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōita Prefecture|ja|大分県|12=draft|12=draft}}, Japan.<ref>[http://wakamiyahachimansha.com/ Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine]</ref> The shrine held the rank of {{ill|Ken-sha|ja|旧県社|12=draft|12=draft}} under the old Shinto shrine ranking system.
== Deities Enshrined == * Ōsasazaki no Mikoto (大鷦鷯命) - {{ill|Emperor Nintoku|ja|仁徳天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}. * Uji no Waki Iratsuko (菟道稚郎子) - A son of {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|ja|応神天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} and half-brother to Emperor Nintoku. * '''Urehime''' (宇礼姫) * '''Kurehime''' (久礼姫)
== History == According to tradition, the shrine was established in {{ill|Kanwa|ja|寛和|12=draft|12=draft}} 1 (985 CE) when {{ill|Ki no Kanesada|ja|紀兼貞|12=draft|12=draft}}, under imperial order, brought four deity statues from {{ill|Iwashimizu Hachimangū|ja|石清水八幡宮|12=draft|12=draft}} to a location in Kashiwajima, a village in the {{ill|Bungo Province|ja|豊後国|12=draft|12=draft}}. These statues were originally carved by {{ill|Prince Atsumi|ja|敦実親王|12=draft|12=draft}}, the ninth son of {{ill|Emperor Uda|ja|宇多天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, from white sandalwood. The statues were consecrated at {{ill|Ninna-ji|ja|仁和寺|12=draft|12=draft}} in 918 before being enshrined at Iwashimizu Hachimangū.<ref name="history">[http://wakamiyahachimansha.com/history/index.html About Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine] Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine</ref>
The shrine was relocated several times, first to its present site in Hamada during {{ill|Tenki|ja|天喜|12=draft|12=draft}} 5 (1057), then to Nakamura in {{ill|Jōan|ja|承安|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 (1173), and finally to its current location in {{ill|Kareki|ja|嘉暦|12=draft|12=draft}} 1 (1326). In 1873, it was ranked as a {{ill|Gō-sha|ja|郷社|12=draft|12=draft}}, and in 1921 it was promoted to the rank of {{ill|Ken-sha|ja|県社|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="history" />
When the shrine moved to Nakamura in 1173, it was granted permission by {{ill|Fujiwara no Tomomichi|ja|藤原伊通|12=draft|12=draft}} and oversaw by {{ill|Bungo Province Governor|ja|豊後国司|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Namba Yoritsuke|ja|難波頼輔|12=draft|12=draft}}, to host a market. This event, later linked to the shrine’s {{ill|Hōjō-e|ja|放生会|12=draft|12=draft}} ceremony, developed into a significant cattle and horse market, recognized as one of {{ill|Japan's Three Great Cattle and Horse Markets|ja|日本三大牛馬市|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{PDFlink|[http://wakamiyahachimansha.com/kintakayama/shaho/kintakayama005.pdf Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine Newsletter, Vol. 5]}} Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine Office, October 1, 2017</ref> Even in 1950, around 2,000 livestock were sold annually.<ref>[http://www.onsenkenoita-ch.com/charms/detail/1286 Records from 1950] Ōita Prefecture Tourism Channel</ref>
== Shrine Buildings == === Sub-Shrines === * {{ill|Wakan Shōgun Shrine|ja|和漢将軍社|12=draft|12=draft}} - Dedicated to {{ill|Kitsuki Chikashige|ja|木付親重|12=draft|12=draft}}, the first head of the {{ill|Kitsuki clan|ja|木付氏|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>[http://wakamiyahachimansha.com/precinct/index.html Grounds of Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine] Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine</ref>
== Festivals and Annual Events == * {{ill|Saitan-sai|ja|歳旦祭|12=draft|12=draft}} - January 1 * Spring Ancestral Festival - During the spring {{ill|Higan|ja|彼岸|12=draft|12=draft}} * Spring Grand Festival & {{ill|Otaue Matsuri|ja|御田植祭|12=draft|12=draft}} - April 6 * Mid-Autumn Festival & Market - Sunday near September 15 * Autumn Ancestral Festival - During the autumn Higan * {{ill|Niiname-sai|ja|新嘗祭|12=draft|12=draft}} - November 23 * Annual Festival - First weekend of December<ref name="event" />
== Cultural Properties == * {{ill|Ōita Prefecture Designated Intangible Folk Cultural Properties|ja|大分県指定無形民俗文化財|12=draft|12=draft}} ** Wakamiya Dance (若宮楽) - Designated March 22, 1966; performed during the Autumn Ancestral Festival.<ref name="event" /> ** Kitsuki Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine's Otaue Festival - Designated March 24, 2000. * {{ill|Ōita Prefecture Designated Natural Monuments|ja|大分県指定天然記念物|12=draft|12=draft}} ** Kitsuki Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine’s Sacred Forest - Designated April 8, 1980. * Kitsuki City Designated Tangible Cultural Properties ** Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine’s Great Plaque - Designated April 13, 1973. ** Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine’s Ridge Tags - Designated April 13, 1973. ** Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine’s Stone Structures - Including a torii from 1643, designated May 10, 1999.<ref>[http://www.city.kitsuki.lg.jp/soshiki/24/kitukitiiki-siteibunnkazaiitiran.html Kitsuki Regional Cultural Properties List] Kitsuki City</ref>
== References == {{reflist}}
== External Links == * [http://wakamiyahachimansha.com/ Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine Official Website] * [http://www.city.kitsuki.lg.jp/modules/itemmanager/index.php?like=0&level=4&genreid=8&itemid=160&storyid=1058 Intangible Cultural Heritage of Kitsuki Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine]
