When the shrine moved to Nakamura in 1173, it was granted permission by {{ill|Fujiwara no Tomomichi|ja|藤原伊通|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Tomomichi|qq=}} and oversaw by {{ill|Bungo Province Governor|ja|豊後国司|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bungo Province Governor|qq=}}, {{ill|Namba Yoritsuke|ja|難波頼輔|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Namba Yoritsuke|qq=}}, to host a market. This event, later linked to the shrine’s [[:en:Life release|Hōjō-e]] ceremony, developed into a significant cattle and horse market, recognized as one of {{ill|Japan's Three Great Cattle and Horse Markets|ja|日本三大牛馬市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japan's Three Great Cattle and Horse Markets|qq=}}.<ref>{{PDFlink|[http://wakamiyahachimansha.com/kintakayama/shaho/kintakayama005.pdf Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine Newsletter, Vol. 5]}} Wakamiya Hachiman Shrine Office, October 1, 2017</ref> Even in 1950, around 2,000 livestock were sold annually.<ref>[http://www.onsenkenoita-ch.com/charms/detail/1286 Records from 1950] Ōita Prefecture Tourism Channel</ref>
